<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-537-603  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 537 603.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  Oct 1990 v41 n10 p24(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fighting crime with computer networks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powers, A. Curtis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US criminal justice system's data sharing differs in circuitsand counties, but as the growth of crime increases, so does theamount of crime data.andP;  Florida's Criminal Justice InformationSystems (CJIS) network links all the judicial agencies in the 8thCircuit's six counties and an integrated network, powered bysupermicro and superminicomputers from Nixdorf Computer.andO;Florida's CJIS has standardized applications, due to theflexibility of Unix.andP;  Agencies are able to view a case status atany time, with every offender's criminal history on filecircuit-wide.andP;  In 1990, the CJIS encompasses every process in thecircuit's administration of criminal justice.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FloridaNetworksLaw EnforcementInformation SystemsMISData ProcessingApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>